The Telegraph - Calcutta : Sports

 Sunday, June 26, 2005 

 Lisbon: Uniao Leiria midfielder Hugo Cunha collapsed and died during a game with friends on Saturday, Lusa news agency reported. Club doctor Amilcar Silva said no health problems had previously shown up during examinations of 28-year-old Cunha.

 Cunha collapsed during a morning game with friends at Montemor-o-Novo, about 70 km (45 miles) east of Lisbon. He was dead on arrival at hospital from an apparent cardio-respiratory arrest, Lusa said.

 London: England and Real Madrid striker Michael Owen married his childhood sweetheart Louise Bonsall at a private ceremony in Flintshire, North Wales, on Friday. Only family and close friends were invited to the wedding which was held in a hotel close to their home. The couple will hold the blessings in a marquee in the grounds of the couple?s mansion near the village of Northop.

 The 25-year-old footballer, who became a household name in the 1998 World Cup, had met Bonsall while the two were pupils at Hawarden High School. The couple have a two-year-old daughter named Gemma Rose.

 New Delhi: Indian cueists came back from behind to upset favourites China 2-1 in the semi-finals of the Asian Open invitational snooker championship at Shinjhen (China). They will face Thailand in Sunday?s summit clash.

 Manan Chandra displayed fine skills but failed to overcome the challenge of Ding Junhai in the opening rubber but his fighting spirit rubbed off on his two experienced teammates. According to information received here, former IBSF world champion Pankaj Advani levelled scores defeating Jian Zhong 3-1. National and Asian champion Alok Kumar kept his nerves to edge past Jin Long 3-2 to seal the tie. Alok earlier went down 1-4 to Paithoon Phonbun of Thailand in the bronze medal play-off match for the individual event.

 Beijing: China slapped two-year suspensions on 12 weightlifters for fradulent dope tests and banned their coaches from participating in the sport for life. All 12 are women weightlifters from central Hubei province who were involved in forging identity papers in an effort to circumvent drug tests, the Xinhua news agency reported. Hubei weightlifting team coaches Xi Hanxiang and Liu Shaojun were given life bans by the Chinese state general administration of sports, the leading sports governmental body, the report said.

 Six of the women were suspected of taking illegal substances to enhance performance, while six other weightlifters using the fake identification papers stood in for them in doping tests. 

 New Delhi: Railways will be looking to lay their hands on the national women?s hockey championship trophy for the 20th time when the 53rd edition gets underway here on Monday.

 The final is scheduled to come off on July 11.

 New Delhi: India?s Shruti Dhawan, the fourth seed, moved into the quarter finals of the women?s meet in Alcobaca, Portugal, on Saturday beating Briton Kirsty Wooley 6-4, 6-3 in the second round, according to information received here on aturday.

 Poonam Reddy lost to Briton Melissa Berry 3-6, 3-6.

 In doubles, Shruti and Poonam lost to Georgian Sofia Kvatsaiba and French Carli Petit 6-4, 4-6, 0-6.

